Why is less distance better?

Austin Stephen

7/8/2021

TLDR:

  1. Offense distance accounts for most of the negative relationship with wins.
  2. Three point percentage is not the cause.
  3. Field goal percentage is not the cause.
  4. Offensive rebounds are not the cause.
  5. Turnovers are not the cause.
  6. (Most Interesting) There is a strong positive correlation with assists per game and wins. Also, there is a strong positive correlation with assists per game and distance. This is the opposite of what we observed with wins and distance per game. Meaning this had to be outweighed by some other factor I can’t find for the negative relationship of interest to exist.

Why is there an inverse correlation with wins and distance?

y = 121.6 + -4.73
p-value: .00018 and adj r-squared: .053

2018

HOU the best team by record has a cluster of players that run less than .5 a miles a game. However, NYK has no players who run under .75 miles a game.

2017

I don’t really see any relationship in 2017.

2016

GSW was the best team and has no players under .5 so essentially the opposite of the 2019 trend with HOU.

Offensive distance accounts for most of the association with wins

Linear model w ~ offense_distance
p-value: 2.4 *10-5
adj r-squared: 0.065

Linear model w ~ defense_distance
p-value: 0.048
adj r-squared: 0.012

Significant relationship between distance on offense and wins. A negative or neutral relationship between distance on defense and wins. This means it is probably linked to some type of offensive statistic.

How distance relates with other offensive statistics

Three Point Percentage

There appears to be a slight positive or no relationship with three point shooting and distance but this is in the opposite direction of the trend with distance and wins. This is impressive because three point shooting is very strongly linked to wins which means the association we saw with distance overcame this relationship.

Field Goal Percentage

Shooting percentage appears to have no relationship with team distance and is clearly linked to winning games as expected.

Offensive Rebounds

Appears to be a slight negative correlation between offensive rebounds and distance which is initially promising. However, offensive rebounds has a negative association with wins so this acts to counteract the net effect of distance we are looking to explain. Also, we know getting offensive rebounds does not make a team worse so it must have to do with missing more shots enables more offensive rebounds. Overall, this does not help explain the effect.

Turnovers

No relationship.

Assists

Assists and distance:
p-value: 4.7 * 10^-8
r-squared: 0.118

Assists and wins:
p-value: 5.854e-05 r-squared: 0.06574

There is a significant positive relationship between distance and assists. Also, there is a significant positive relationship between assists and wins. This is the opposite of what we would expect to see because it means distance had to overcome this relationship to get the negative correlation we saw.

Total passes
